<DOC><DOCNO> AP890908-0226 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1011EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-UAL     09-08 0333</FIRST><SECOND>PM-UAL,0349</SECOND><HEAD>Say Big Texas Investor, Buyout Specialist Kohlberg Kravis Might Bid</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Billionaire investor Robert Bass and takeoverfirm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Co. have contacted United Airlines'Machinists union about bidding for parent company UAL Corp., theWall Street Journal reported today.   Overtures from Bass and Kohlberg suggested a pilot-led $6.75billion offer backed by management could face unexpected competitionin the bidding struggle for UAL, one of the nation's leadingairlines and a prime takeover target.   United's Machinist union has not supported the pilot-managementproposal.   UAL's board also is considering a $6.19 billion offer from LosAngeles investor Marvin Davis, but there have been rumors that hehas started selling his stake in the company, an indication he mightscrap his takeover effort.   UAL stock, which fell $5.12{ a share on the Davis rumor Thursday,was up $2.75 a share to $284.50 in early New York Stock Exchangetrading today.   The Journal quoted Machinists union vice president John Peterpaulas saying a Bass-led group is seeking a meeting to discuss whetherthe machinists would be interesting in supporting a bid.   Peterpaul also was quoted as saying Kohlberg Kravis has expressedinterest as well. Both contacts were described as preliminary and nopossible purchase amount was disclosed.   The bidding for Chicago-based UAL began several weeks ago with anoffer by Davis and quickly escalated into one of the biggesttakeover sagas of 1989, driving up the company's stock price onspeculation that higher offers would emerge.   Bass is a leading corporate dealmaker from Texas with interestsin oil, financial services, real estate, publishing and investmentsin several well-known companies.   Kohlberg is a New York-based investment house that helped pioneerthe takeover strategy known as the leveraged buyout, in whichcompanies are bought with borrowed money repaid through earnings orasset sales of the target company. Kohlberg paid nearly $25 billionin mostly borrowed money to buy RJR Nabisco Inc. earlier this year,the biggest takeover in history.</TEXT></DOC>